Hexagonal binning

Source: R/2d.R
hex_binning.Rd

This function generates the hexagonal object.

Usage

hex_binning(data, bin1 = 2, s1 = -0.1, s2 = -0.1, r2)

Arguments

data

A tibble that contains embedding components.

bin1

Number of bins along the x axis.

s1

The x-coordinate of the hexagonal grid starting point.

s2

The y-coordinate of the hexagonal grid starting point.

r2

The range of the original second embedding component.

Value

A object that contains numeric vector that contains bins along the x and y axes respectively, all hexagonal bin centroids (centroids), hexagonal coordinates of the full grid(hex_poly), embedding components with their corresponding hexagon IDs (data_hb_id), hex bins with their corresponding standardise counts (std_cts), total number of hex bins(tot_bins), number of non-empty hex bins (non_bins) and points within each hexagon (pts_bins).

Examples

range_umap2 <- diff(range(s_curve_noise_umap$UMAP2))
num_bins_x <- 3
hex_binning(data = s_curve_noise_umap_scaled, bin1 = num_bins_x, s1 = -0.1,
s2 = -0.1, r2 = range_umap2)
